SPORT remains one of the most powerful tools to bring together different nations, countries, ethnic groups – uniting people from different backgrounds without any need for labels. Gauteng Premier David Makhura has therefore taken this very route to unite people and stop xenophobia and racism, with the launch of the second annual Social Cohesion Games to be played at several venues around the province.The tournament was launched at Killarney Cine Centre in Joburg yesterday. In attendance were Zambia legend Kalusha Bwalya, now a Caf executive member, as well as South African legends such as Doctor Khumalo. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");var viewReq = new Array();function vu(u) {var i=new Image();i.src=u.replace("&amp;","&");viewReq.push(i);}vu("https://securepubads.g.doubleclick.net/pcs/view?xai\x3dAKAOjsuNHUNIx0ryi2qjclidqksowNFcE7H2RJlpVWKaC5qAouTa12aJuMJnkGJftcC5MCEnLYpIYwycNQbt1RDQ_KmGz-mTaeUSr0ugzVP_hhUQnvjJBix-jKwkNcwCcCJHGTUg-57cq58tabW3vmLq0II0Dj8_gsKQv2x7iHGobgpZ7ZjFKRxZPfjCUFq4k7iHMIm4wHNT2f-Tg-mXVFZns39TnrSuT0PdvG8mGT5IJzSg40ygVv-FP6kcbMDb-klHs2d8N_XDSHlgQ0VkMKn40g\x26sig\x3dCg0ArKJSzMCNlJw2gUdqEAE\x26urlfix\x3d1\x26adurl\x3d")

   
