<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The Last 16 round of the games will take place at Westbury Stadium this weekend, with the final scheduled for 15 April at Ace Ntsoelengoe Stadium in Randfontein.Makhura said: “Our message is ‘say no to racism’. There are incidents of racism happening everywhere, which shows we still carry that past with us.“And this year we also want to say no to abuse of women as well as xenophobia. “Gauteng attracts people from all over the world. Many of them, especially those from Southern Africa, come here as soccer players.He added: “With xenophobia, people are fighting, blaming each other and that has been a huge concern. When you have migrants from Europe they are seen as job creators and when you have African migrants, they are seen as a problem. “We have to change that mentality, this is our continent – everybody who is here needs to make a positive contribution.”Zambia’s eighth most capped player Bwalya said he planned to attend the games this year after missing the first edition last year. He said: “What the premier said is important. It is heart-warming for me to be here and feel welcome. “This year I want to be part of this initiative. To have this special day to bring people together, as Nelson Mandela said, is fantastic.”Legends who will take part include Jabu Mahlangu, Steve Lekoelea, Innocent Chikoya, Edelbert Dinah, Tebogo Moloi and Frank Makua.